{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637441"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:42:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:42:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17662"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17662"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.42,0.13,0.17,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10376"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78236"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10376"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17662"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63645"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"9830"},{"type":"tags","id":"9869"},{"type":"tags","id":"9871"},{"type":"tags","id":"10529"},{"type":"tags","id":"10532"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24264"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24299"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78236"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EInterstitial fluid fills the spaces between cells in tissues throughout the body and plays a crucial role in maintaining cellular homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical protein concentration in interstitial fluid compared to plasma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Equal to plasma protein concentration","Lower than plasma protein concentration","Higher than plasma protein concentration","Zero protein concentration","Twice the plasma protein concentration"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprotein concentration in interstitial fluid is lower than that of plasma\u003C/strong\u003E. This lower concentration results from the limited permeability of capillary walls to proteins due to their large molecular size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eequal protein concentration\u003C/strong\u003E would be impossible because capillary walls act as a selective barrier that restricts protein movement, preventing complete equilibration between plasma and interstitial fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigher protein concentration\u003C/strong\u003E cannot occur as proteins must first pass through capillary walls from plasma, and there is no mechanism to concentrate them in the interstitial space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ezero protein concentration\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as some proteins, particularly smaller ones, do cross the capillary wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwice the plasma protein concentration\u003C/strong\u003E is physiologically impossible as proteins cannot concentrate in interstitial fluid above plasma levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe protein concentration difference between plasma and interstitial fluid is a key determinant of fluid movement across capillary walls according to Starling forces. This difference creates an important oncotic pressure gradient that helps maintain intravascular volume.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Interstitial fluid is formed by filtration from capillaries under the influence of Starling forces.","The protein concentration in interstitial fluid is much lower than plasma due to limited permeability of capillaries to proteins.","Interstitial fluid composition is similar to plasma for small molecules but differs significantly for proteins and other large molecules."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63645"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17662"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63645"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T22:42:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T22:43:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10376"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78236"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.